        "## 5.24 Summary\n",
        "\n",
        "Difference equations provide the mathematical language for time-series dynamics. In AR models, the same recurrence controls deterministic paths, impulse responses, and autocovariance decay. Real roots produce monotone or alternating decay. Complex roots produce damped oscillations. Repeated roots create polynomial-exponential behavior. The companion matrix connects the theory to linear algebra: stability is an eigenvalue condition.\n",
